Take the Global Superstore data set.

Add the columuns are Profit Margin, Cost columuns in the Superstore data set. 
Import the data set into the Power bi. 

Financial KPI Columns Added. 
Profit Margin 
Profit Margin = DIVIDE([Profit], [Sales])  

#It will fill all the columns without the below errors for the Caluculation=IFERROR(G2/F2,0)
Sales is in column F
Profit is in column G
You want Profit Margin in column H
Calculates Profit ÷ Sales
Avoids #DIV/0! errors
Is equivalent to Power BI’s DIVIDE()
Profit Margin was calculated in Excel using a dynamic formula with error handling to ensure accurate results even when sales values are zero. The formula was auto-filled across the dataset using Excel table functionality for scalability and consistency.

Cost (Optional but Powerful)
Cost = [Sales] - [Profit]

#Calculation Steps:
=IFERROR(S2 - V2, 0)
Sales = column S
Profit = column V
Cost was derived in Excel by subtracting Profit from Sales using a row-wise formula with error handling. The calculation was auto-filled across the dataset using Excel table functionality to maintain consistency and scalability.

KPI MEASURES Taken. 
Total Sales = SUM('Table'[Sales])
Total Profit = SUM('Table'[Profit])
Average Margin = AVERAGE('Table'[Profit Margin])
KPI measures such as Total Sales, Total Profit, and Profit Margin were calculated using a centralized fact table containing transactional data. Supporting dimension tables for date, product, and region were used to enable filtering and drill-down analysis, following a star schema design.

STEP 1: Import Dataset
Open Power BI Desktop
Home → Get Data → Excel / CSV
Load your dataset
Click Load

Make sure these columns exist:
Sales
Profit
Order Date

STEP 2: Create KPI MEASURES (IMPORTANT: Measures, not columns)
Go to Data view or Report view → Modeling → New measure
Total Sales (Measure) Total Sales = SUM('Fact_Sales'[Sales])
Total Profit (Measure) Total Profit = SUM('Fact_Sales'[Profit])
Profit Margin (Measure) Profit Margin = DIVIDE([Total Profit], [Total Sales], 0)

This:
Prevents divide-by-zero errors
Updates dynamically with slicers

STEP 3: Format the Measures (Very Important)
Total Sales
Format: Currency
Decimal places: 0 or 2
Total Profit
Format: Currency
Profit Margin
Format: Percentage
Decimal places: 1–2

STEP 4: Create KPI CARDS (Dashboard Top Section)
Go to Report View  - Insert Card visual
Card 1
Field: Total Sales
Title: Total Sales
Card 2
Field: Total Profit
Title: Total Profit
Card 3
Field: Profit Margin
Title: Profit Margin

KPI measures for Total Sales, Total Profit, and Profit Margin were created using DAX measures to ensure dynamic calculation. These KPIs were displayed using card visuals at the top of the dashboard, allowing real-time performance monitoring based on user-selected filters such as date, region, and category.

ADD TREND CHART: SALES OVER TIME
Choose the Right Visual
Go to Report View
Select Line chart from Visualizations
Line chart = best for time trends (never bar).

Add Fields (MOST IMPORTANT PART)
Axis (X-axis) Drag: Order Date
Use Date hierarchy Year, Quarter, Month FOR (best practice): Use Month-Year column (if created)

Values (Y-axis) Drag: Total Sales (Measure)

Fix Date Sorting (Very Common Issue)
If using Month-Year:
Select Month-Year column
Column tools → Sort by Column
Sort by Order Date or YearMonth number
This prevents Jan–Dec being scrambled.

Add Context (Optional but Strong)
Tooltips Add: Total Profit, Profit Margin. 
Now hovering shows quality of sales, not just quantity.

A line chart was used to visualize Total Sales over time, enabling trend and seasonality analysis. Date hierarchies allow drill-down from year to month, helping stakeholders understand sales growth patterns and performance fluctuations.

ADD CATEGORY BREAKDOWN (BAR CHART)
Choose the Right Visual
Go to Report View
Select Clustered bar chart
Bar (horizontal) is best for category comparison and long names.

Add Fields (Critical Setup)
Axis (Y-axis) Drag: Category 
Values (X-axis) Drag: Total Sales


This shows revenue contribution by category

Optional (Highly Recommended): Profit View
To deepen analysis, you can:
Add Total Profit to Values OR
Duplicate the chart and switch to Total Profit
Sales shows volume, Profit shows quality.

Sort for Insight (Very Important)
Click the chart
Three dots (⋯) → Sort by Total Sales
Sort → Descending

Top-performing categories appear first.
Format the Chart (Clean & Professional)
Data Labels On Display units: Auto
Axis Titles
X-axis: Total Sales
Y-axis: Category

Add Drill Capability (Optional but Impressive)
Enable Drill Down:
Category → Sub-Category
Allows users to explore deeper without cluttering the page.

Placement Tip (Layout)
Place below or beside Sales Trend
Keep consistent width with trend chart

A clustered bar chart was used to compare Total Sales across product categories, enabling quick identification of top-performing and underperforming segments. Sorting and drill-down features allow deeper analysis at the sub-category level.

